      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Extracting text from images and documents at scale remains a persistent challenge for API teams, often involving trade-offs between accuracy, latency, and cost. Traditional OCR solutions can struggle with varied layouts, low-quality scans, or high-volume throughput, leading to bottlenecks in data pipelines. Nanonets OCR S addresses these pain points by offering a model fine-tuned for production environments, where reliability and speed are non-negotiable."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Built on a transformer architecture with F16 (half-precision) optimization, Nanonets OCR S balances computational efficiency with robust text recognition across multiple languages and document types. This blog post details how to integrate, configure, and leverage this model in your stack, covering performance benchmarks, cost structures, and real-world deployment patterns. You'll gain actionable insights to implement OCR that meets enterprise-grade demands without sacrificing developer experience."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Capabilities of Nanonets OCR S"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Nanonets OCR S is engineered for scenarios requiring consistent text extraction from heterogeneous sources, such as invoices, receipts, and handwritten notes. It supports over 50 languages, including Latin, Cyrillic, and CJK scripts, with a focus on preserving layout integrity—critical for structured documents like forms or tables. The model's F16 precision reduces memory footprint by approximately 50% compared to FP32 alternatives, enabling faster inference on GPUs without significant accuracy loss, typically maintaining over 95% character-level accuracy on benchmark datasets."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Key features include automatic rotation correction, noise reduction for low-quality scans, and bounding box detection for localized text regions. Unlike general-purpose vision models, Nanonets OCR S is optimized for OCR-specific tasks, minimizing false positives in cluttered backgrounds. For API teams, this translates to fewer preprocessing steps and more reliable outputs, as the model handles edge cases like skewed images or variable lighting conditions internally."
          }
        ]
      },
